identificationModule.briefTitle: Jump Start on the Go: Improving Resiliency and the Social-Emotional Development of At-Risk Preschool Children
identificationModule.officialTitle: Jump Start on the Go: Improving Resiliency and the Social-Emotional Development of At-Risk Preschool Children in Childcare Centers Using a Mobile Application

descriptionModule.briefSummary: The purpose of this study is to test the Jump Start on the Go (JS Go), an app-based program and see how helpful it is at improving resiliency and behavior support within childcare settings.

armGroups.label: Jump Start on the Go Group
armGroups.description: Participants will be in this group for a total of up to 12 months. These participants will receive the intervention via a mobile app.
interventionNames: Behavioral: Jump Start on the Go

armGroups.label: Jump Start plus Coronavirus Support Group
armGroups.description: Participants will be in this group for a total of up to 12 months.
interventionNames: Behavioral: Jump Start Plus Coronavirus Support

interventions.name: Jump Start on the Go
interventions.description: Centers will receive the Jump Start On The Go mental health program via a mobile app. This will entail receiving 12-24 mental health consultation sessions in which a licensed mental health consultant will use a mobile app that will provide directors and teachers with access to information such as videos, infographics, and an Artificial Intelligence Chatbot on how to work with children with challenging behaviors. Participants will receive the intervention once per week for up to 1 hour.
armGroupLabels: Jump Start on the Go Group

interventions.name: Jump Start Plus Coronavirus Support
interventions.description: The Jump Start Plus Coronavirus Support intervention is a resiliency program that provides behavior management and safety programs administered weekly via zoom.
armGroupLabels: Jump Start plus Coronavirus Support Group

primaryOutcomes.measure: Change in classroom practices as measured by Health Environment Rating Scale
primaryOutcomes.description: The Health Environment Rating Scale is a measure with a range of score from 0 to 70 with higher score indicating better classroom practices.

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in child behaviors as measured by Devereux Early Childhood Assessments (DECA)
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Devereux Early Childhood Assessments is a measure with a range of score from 0 to 100 with higher score on Behavior Concerns indicating more problem behaviors.

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in child behaviors as measured by Strengths and Difficulties Questionnaire (SDQ)
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Strengths and Difficulties Questionnaire is a total difficulties score that ranges from 0 to 40 with higher scores indicating less child behavior concerns.

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in resiliency as measured by Brief Resiliency Coping Scale
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Brief Resiliency Coping Scale is a total score that ranges from 4 to 20 with higher scores indicating higher levels of coping

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in stress as measured by Childcare Worker Job Stress Index
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Childcare Worker Job Stress Index is a total score that ranges from 22 to 110 with higher scores indicating higher levels of stress

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in stress as measured by Everyday Stressors Index
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Everyday Stressors Index is a total score that ranges from 0 to 80 with higher scores indicating higher levels of stress.

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Change in satisfaction as measured by Teacher Opinion and Satisfaction survey
secondaryOutcomes.description: The Teacher Opinion survey is a measure with a range of score from 12 to 44 with higher score indicating better self-efficacy as it relates to teaching practices.

eligibilityModule.eligibilityCriteria:
Centers Inclusion Criteria:

1. Centers must have \>30 children ages 2-to-5
2. Center must serve low income families
3. Centers must reflect the ethnic diversity of the Miami Dade County Public School System (60% Hispanic, 20% Non-Hispanic Black, 20% Non-Hispanic White).

Participants Inclusion Criteria:

1. Participants must speak English or Spanish or Creole
2. Parents must have a child enrolled in the childcare center that is participating in the study.
3. Children ages 2-5: Parent reported data (name, Date of Birth, behaviors)

Exclusion Criteria:

1. any participants who do not speak English or Spanish or Creole.
